{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/economic-order-quantity-with-r-f511bfeec400", "time": 1683002634.476584, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/economic-order-quantity-with-r-f511bfeec400/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Economic Order Quantity with R. Exploring the \u201cSCperf\u201d R package | by Roberto Salazar | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Economic Order Quantity with R", "description": "Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) is an inventory planning and managing measurement used in Operations, Supply Chain, and Logistics departments within business and organizations. It represents the\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/SCperf/SCperf.pdf", "anchor_text": "SCperf", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/rsalaza4/R-for-Industrial-Engineering/blob/master/Inventory%20Planning%20and%20Managing/Economic%20Order%20Quantity.R", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/roberto-salazar-reyna/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://robertosalazarr.medium.com/", "anchor_text": "profile", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) is an inventory planning and managing measurement used in Operations, Supply Chain, and Logistics departments within business and organizations. It represents the optimum quantity of an item to be purchased per order to minimize the combined ordering and holding costs. It helps to determine the frequency of orders required to satisfy a given annual demand.", "*May or may not be considered.", "The chart above shows the behavior of the total cost curve as a function of the order cost curve and the holding cost line. The order cost curve falls with the increase in ordering volume due to purchasing on economies of scale. On the other hand, the holding cost line increases linearly as the inventory level grows. The intersection between the order cost curve and the holding cost line represents the EOQ.", "The SCperf package from R contains several functions for multiple inventory planning and managing methods. For the following example, let\u2019s consider these values for the EOQ model variables: D = 2400 units, S = $10 per order, H = $0.3 per unit per year, and ss = 0 units, respectively.", "Let\u2019s take look at the R code!", "Now that we have obtained relevant information about how the supply chain analyst must plan and manage the inventory appropriately, let\u2019s build a graph to keep track of its availability throughout the year and to identify the replenishment time.", "The graph above confirmed the results previously obtained. The supply chain analyst must place 6 replenishment orders of 400 units each throughout the year during the months 0, 2, 4, 6, 8 and 10 since it takes exactly 2 months for the inventory to stock out.", "On the other hand, if we had assumed a safety stock of 50 units (ss = 50), the inventory graph would have looked like this:", "As seen on the graph above, the only difference between this and the original inventory graph was an upper shift on the y-axis, corresponding to the safety stock. The number of units per order (Q), the demand rate, and the total number of orders remained the same, respectively.", "Inventory planning and managing represents a critical task for every organization and business on today\u2019s highly competitive world, which should be used as a competitive advantage to achieve optimum production levels at the lowest costs possible.", "The SCperf R package includes multiple functions that provide relevant information to supply chain analysts \u2014 with just a few lines of code \u2014 for them to be able to plan and manage inventory levels appropriately.", "While there are other inventory planning and managing software available, R represents a great tool for obtaining relevant information for simple inventory planning and managing tasks. Having stored an inventory planning and managing R code in your personal code library could save you a significant amount of time by just having to input the values of the respective EOQ variables.", "If you found this article useful, feel welcome to download my personal codes on GitHub. You can also email me directly at rsalaza4@binghamton.edu and find me on LinkedIn. Interested in learning more about data analytics, data science and machine learning applications in the engineering field? Explore my previous articles by visiting my Medium profile. Thanks for reading.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff511bfeec400&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Feconomic-order-quantity-with-r-f511bfeec400&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Feconomic-order-quantity-with-r-f511bfeec400&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Feconomic-order-quantity-with-r-f511bfe